    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1876-02-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1876-02-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="243"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d243">
                <head>No. 233.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Fish</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Moran</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1876-02-15">
                            <hi rend="italic">February</hi> 15, 1876</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 30.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Your dispatch No. 53, under date of January 5
                    ultimo, has been received. It informs the Department of the transmission by you
                    to Mr. Corvo, the minister for foreign affairs at Lisbon, of a copy of the
                    President’s last annual message to Congress, and incloses a translation of a <pb
                        facs="0490" n="434" xml:id="pg_434"/> note received from Mr. Corvo,
                    acknowledging its receipt, and also a copy of your note in reply thereto.</p>
                <p>The expression of the deep sense of appreciation of the Portuguese government,
                    contained in Mr. Corvo’s note, of the President’s recognition in his message of
                    the Portuguese act of emancipation of April 29, 1875, has been received with
                    satisfaction by the President, and he directs me to express the gratification
                    that will attend the actual emancipation of slavery in the Portuguese colonies
                    as provided by the act in question.</p>
                <p>Your note to Mr. Corvo upon the subject meets with the approval of the
                    Department.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>HAMILTON FISH.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
